[3] Nepal
Date: Wed 20 Feb 2019
From: Sher Bahadur Pun <drsherbdr@yahoo.com> [edited]


According to the Epidemiology & Disease Control Division (EDCD), from the beginning of the January until 15 Feb 2019, at least 1334 patients who presented with influenza-like illness (ILI) were tested to identify/confirm influenza viruses at the national influenza center (through different hospitals). During this time period, at least 8 (0.6%) people died from flu related complications. Of these, 567 (43%) were tested positive for influenza A(H1N1)pdm09, while 23 (1.8%) and 73 (5.5%) were identified as A(H3) and type B influenza virus, respectively. 561 (42%) out of 1334 samples tested negative for influenza virus. Some of the patients (8.2%) who tested positive for type A influenza were found untypeable by available primers. Currently, national influenza center is employing primers for H1, (H1N1)pdm09, H3, H5a, H5b, and H7N9 subtypes among ILI clinical samples.

Here, a major concern is that whether these untypeable strains are new or zoonotic influenza that need further attention, which may not so far be included in the laboratory testing.

--
Sher Bahadur Pun, MD
Clinical Research Unit,
Sukraraj Tropical and Infectious Disease Hospital,
Kathmandu, Nepal
<drsherbdr@yahoo.com>

[ProMED-mail thanks Dr Sher Bahadur Pun for his update on seasonal influenza in Nepal. A small percentage of ILI or severe respiratory illness (SARI) samples may not be typeable on real-time PCR assays for a number of reasons, in addition to the possibility of emergence of a new or novel virus; the viral RNA in the sample may be insufficient --primers/probes are highly specific against the sequences and small changes in the viral genome may cause a mismatch, untypeable samples must be referred to WHO collaborating Centers for further testing. - Mod.UBA

