[4] France
Date: Wed 6 Feb 2019 21:26 CET
Source: CNews [in French, trans Corr.SB, edited]
https://www.cnews.fr/france/2019-02-06/lepidemie-de-grippe-deja-fait-plus-de-1000-morts-810438


The epidemic of influenza intensifies in metropolitan France and has already caused more than 1000 deaths, according to the health agency Public Health France. "About 1100 deaths of all ages are attributable to influenza, since the beginning of surveillance," it notes [Wed 6 Feb 2019] in its weekly bulletin based on figures as of 20 Jan 2019.

All indicators of influenza activity are increasing (consultations with general practitioners, emergency room visits, hospitalizations, etc), whereas the epidemic had already spread to all regions the previous week.

Among more than 12 000 patients who presented to the emergency last week [week of 28 Jan 2019], 1823 were hospitalized (+70% compared to the previous week), according to the Oscour network. These hospitalizations mainly concern people aged 75 years or older (43%) and children under 5 years of age (15%).

More generally, the share of hospitalizations for influenza or influenza-like illness [ILI] among hospitalizations is 30/1000, a "very strong increase" (18/1000, the previous week), underlines the health agency SpFrance.

Since 1 Nov 2018, 630 serious cases of influenza (including 139 last week) admitted to intensive care have been reported. Of these, 48 deaths were recorded, all in adults, particularly among those aged 65 and over (33).

In the city, the ILI consultation rate reached 536 per 100 000 inhabitants (+47% compared to the previous week), according to the Sentinel surveillance network.

In the more than 10 000 senior care facilities (nursing homes, long-term care units in hospitals, retirement homes) 160 outbreaks of acute respiratory infections have been attributed to influenza.

Moderate vaccine effectiveness
------------------------------
Among all people at risk, the effectiveness of vaccination in urban medicine is, according to 1st estimates, "moderate" (59%) against the influenza A(H1N1)pdm09 virus and "weak" (19%) against the A(H3N2) virus, says SpFrance.

These preliminary results come from the "Sentinel network that produces an estimate of the effectiveness of the vaccine to avoid an influenza infection leading to a consultation with a general practitioner," says the health agency. "These estimates will be refined in the coming weeks."

The Caribbean is now in the epidemic phase, while Mayotte remains below the epidemic threshold, despite an increase in emergency room visits for influenza or influenza-like illness.

[byline: Marie Aubazac]

