******
[6] United Kingdom
Date: Wed 20 Feb 2019 15:00 GMT
Source: The Guardian [abridged, edited]
https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/feb/20/britons-urged-to-get-flu-vaccine-as-critical-cases-rise-above-2000


Flu has left more than 2000 Britons needing life-or-death treatment in an intensive care unit (ICU) this winter [2018-19], even though the virus is circulating at unusually low levels. Senior doctors said as many people were at risk of dying as during the pandemics of 2009-10 and 2010-11, despite the small numbers contracting the virus. One leading expert said the strain of flu this winter was so virulent that it had left people who were previously fit and healthy critically ill, some of whom hospitals have been unable to save. Those who have not had this year's winter flu vaccine appear to be most at risk.

Pregnant women and adults with a long-term medical condition who contract the virus are most likely to end up struggling to breathe so badly that they could die, said Public Health England (PHE). This strain of flu is following a dangerously different pattern than usual, with comparatively few people visiting their GP about it but large numbers becoming so unwell they risk dying.

In total, 2182 people in the UK have had to be admitted to an ICU or high-dependency unit (HDU) because of flu since the start of October [2018]. That is more than the 2045 who needed such care in the same period last year [2017], when the virus was much more prevalent. Flu has killed 195 this winter [2018-19], though that is down on the 241 deaths that occurred in the same period in 2017-18.

Dr Simon Ashworth, a consultant in intensive care at St Mary's hospital in London, who has specialised in such care for 25 years, said: "This is the worst flu season I have ever known." At least 6 of his ICU's 32 beds have been taken up with flu patients since mid-December [2018]. Ashworth said: "Although the overall incidence of flu reported by Public Health England is, if anything, lower than last year, our experience at St Mary's has been that we have seen more patients with severe influenza requiring intensive care than we saw even in 2010. "Colleagues from other hospitals have reported similar experiences, including those from ECMO [extra corporeal membrane oxygenation] centres, which have reported high levels of activity and running at close to capacity. Our impression is that patients who have ended up in ICU have generally not been vaccinated so even if the vaccine hasn't been completely protective, it has reduced the risk of life-threatening infection."

The most recent flu surveillance data, released by PHE [Public Health England] last [Thu 14 Feb 2019], showed that primary care services, mainly GP surgeries, were seeing low-intensity levels of the virus in the week ending [10 Feb 2019]. Only 23.1 people per 100 000 of population were reporting flu-like symptoms.

[byline: Denis Campbell]

